  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "pVRDDFsQKioJqS6cjF8VxNUDE4k=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "Our Swarm plugin follows the same duplication pattern as the native Switchboard sync, with Swarm substituted for PostgreSQL:\n\n```\nCONNECT (browser)                    SWARM NETWORK\nPGlite (local)                       /bytes (encrypted ops)\n  - operations                         - operation batches (SAME ops)\n  - documents                        Feeds (pointers)\n  - relationships                      - doc/drive/user manifests\n```\n\n**Same 2x duplication pattern** \u2014 operations exist in PGlite AND on Swarm. The structural contract is identical:\n- Local primary (PGlite) for hot reads\n- Durable remote (Swarm instead of PostgreSQL) for recovery and cross-device\n\nWhat changes:\n- **Access control**: API key/auth token -> postage stamp + encryption\n- **Operator**: server-operator-controlled -> decentralized, no single operator\n- **Trust model**: trusted server -> self-sovereign (wallet-based)\n- **Durability model**: row-deletable -> immutable content-addressed chunks\n\nThis is why the Swarm plugin slots into the reactor architecture cleanly \u2014 it preserves the same local+remote shape the SyncManager already expects, just routes traffic through a different channel.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
    }
  },
